        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-07-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-07-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="154" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <head>No. 154.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward
                                        Thornton</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-07-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 4,
                                    1872</date>. (Received July 5.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to your note of yesterday, I
                                have the honor to inform you that as soon as it was announced to Her
                                Majesty’s government that the United States Government was prepared
                                to carry out the survey of <pb facs="0296" n="200" xml:id="pg_200"/>
                                the northwest boundary between the Lake of the Woods and the Rocky
                                Mountains, and that Mr. Archibald Campbell was appointed as
                                commissioner for that purpose, Captain Cameron was also appointed in
                                the same character on the part of Her Majesty’s government. The
                                preparation of the necessary instruments was at once taken in hand,
                                and Captain Cameron was instructed to proceed to Washington for the
                                purpose of putting himself in communication with Mr. Campbell, with
                                a view to arranging the plans for their future proceedings.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>EDWD. THORNTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
